业家正在做些事情，在2021  -  22年，我写了一系列帖子，通过工业家思想的角度来研究各个国家的发展经验： </p><div class="digest-post-embed" data-attrs="{&quot;nodeId&quot;:&quot;7768eb12-ad44-46fc-9757-1606c579f394&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&#8220;The consequences for human welfare involved in questions like these are simply staggering: once one starts to think about them, it is hard to think about anything else.&#8221; &#8212; Robert Lucas On a trip to Turkey in 2018, I read How Asia Works, by Joe Studwell. Despite the fact that it&quot;,&quot;size&quot;:&quot;sm&quot;,&quot;isEditorNode&quot;:true,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;The Developing Country Industrialization series&quot;,&quot;publishedBylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:8243895,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Noah Smith&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Econ blogger&quot;,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/89fd964a-586f-461a-9f5a-ea4587d45728_397x441.png&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;post_date&quot;:&quot;2023-02-10T16:52:28.540Z&quot;,&quot;cover_image&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F931497b0-d155-4bb1-869a-f9aa5b1956d5_640x449.png&quot;,&quot;cover_image_alt&quot;:null,&quot;canonical_url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-developing-country-industrialization&quot;,&quot;section_name&quot;:null,&quot;id&quot;:101947144,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;reaction_count&quot;:129,&quot;comment_count&quot;:75,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Noahpinion&quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F04281755-2cd6-42e5-a496-e69153abebb2_281x281.png&quot;,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false}"></div><p>最壮观的成功案例 - 波兰，马来西亚和其他一些 - 似乎都广泛地符合韩国模式（尽管像中国一样，他们使用的外国直接投资比韩国更多）。因此，我对整个出口制造策略非常看好。</p><p>无论如何，工业家营地还包括著名的哈佛经济学家丹尼·罗德里克（Dani Rodrik）。 2004年，罗德里克（Rodrik）写了一篇名为“ <a href="https://drodrik.scholar.harvard.edu/files/dani-rodrik/files/industrial-policy-twenty-first-century.pdf">二十一世纪的工业政策</a>”的论文，敦促各国促进出口作为发现其比较优势的一种方式。 2007年，他对发展中国家在1960年代和70年代尝试过的“进口替代工业化”策略撰写了<a href="https://rodrik.typepad.com/dani_rodriks_weblog/2007/08/does-import-sub.html">合格的辩护</a>。 <a href="https://drodrik.scholar.harvard.edu/files/dani-rodrik/files/unconditional-convergence-in-manufacturing.pdf">他在2013年指出，</a>国家的制造业往往比其他行业快得多。这表明，发展中国家可以通过增加其全球竞争性制造业的规模来鼓励生产率增长。</p><p>但是在2010年代中期，罗德里克开始怀疑。 2015年，他撰写了一篇名为“ <a href="https://drodrik.scholar.harvard.edu/files/dani-rodrik/files/premature_deindustrialization_revised2.pdf">过早的工业化</a>”的论文，其中他认为“与早期工业化者的经验相比，各国的工业化机会越来越早，收入水平较低”。他认为，就发展中国家而言，自动化不是罪魁祸首。相反，这是全球贸易模式：</p><blockquote><p>明显的替代方法[与技术相反的解释]是贸易和全球化。一个合理的故事将是以下内容。随着发展中国家开放贸易，其制造业受到双重冲击的打击。那些在制造业中没有强大比较优势的人成为制造业的净进口商，扭转了漫长的进口替代过程。此外，发展中国家从发达国家“进口”了工业化……该帐户与发展中国家的就业和产出份额的大大减少（尤其是那些不专门从事制造商）一致。这也有助于解释以下事实：在制造商中具有比较优势的亚洲国家已经幸免了相同的趋势。</p></blockquote><p>基本上，罗德里克（Rodrik）的故事是为何自1960年代以来非洲和拉丁美洲自由化的故事：</p><ol><li><p>亚洲的工业化吸引了大多数富裕世界对制造业需求的需求，而对非洲和拉丁美洲的造成了更少的影响。</p></li><li><p>富裕国家的人们开始购买更多的服务，并且他们对物理产品的需求陷入了停滞，这意味着总体上对制成品的全球需求降低了。</p></li></ol><p>如果这是真的，这是否意味着非洲和拉丁美洲将无法像其他国家一样工业化？也许，但是我有疑问。</p><p>最重要的是，上面的两个效果中的第一个应该是暂时的。一旦中国和其他亚洲国家发展起来，它们将成为对制成品的重要需求来源，就像欧洲，美国，日本，韩国等一样。他们的成本将上升，这意味着他们将寻求从更便宜的地方购买东西。亚洲发展后，非洲将是唯一一个低成本的地区。</p><p>此外，罗德里克（Rodrik）的模型表明，早产的去工业化使制造业的就业份额达到了18.9％，而不是21.5％。它表明，制造业的产出份额现在将达到2015年美元约为22,000美元（今天的美元左右29,000美元）： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg" width="718" height="296" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:296,&quot;width&quot;:718,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:24600,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2c71eaa6-a386-4fb8-ab42-b556b808908c_718x296.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://drodrik.scholar.harvard.edu/files/dani-rodrik/files/premature_deindustrialization_revised2.pdf">Rodrik（2015）</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果以制造业为主导的增长可以将您一路带到人均GDP $ 29,000（现在比阿根廷还要丰富），那么我将这一胜利称为胜利。特别是对于像南亚这样的地方，其人均GDP目前约为6,300美元，即3,700美元的撒哈拉以南非洲。而且，如果制造业可以使您的19％的人口工作，而不是22％，那么这也不是太可怕了。</p><p>因此，当这篇论文问世时，我并不担心。在最糟糕的情况下，这使我对工业主义发展方法的开发方法的乐观程度不那么乐观。</p><p>但是最近，罗德里克（Rodrik）与传奇的约瑟夫·斯蒂格利兹（Joseph Stiglitz）合作，推动了《去工业化论文》的强大（更加悲观）的版本。罗德里克（Rodrik）和斯蒂格利茨（Stiglitz）在最近的一篇题为“ <a href="https://drodrik.scholar.harvard.edu/sites/scholar.harvard.edu/files/dani-rodrik/files/a_new_growth_strategy_for_developing_nations.pdf">发展国家的新增长战略</a>”的文章中，写道，贫穷的国家需要专注于制造业，甚至根本不关注出口，而是专注于绿色能源和非交易服务：</p><blockquote><p> [T]技术变化使制造技能和资本密集型，减少劳动力的劳动力越来越少。这削弱了工业化作为一种​​增长战略的效力……增长战略吸收劳动力的能力同时降低了，因为发展中国家的比较优势至少减弱了……</p><p>美国与中国之间的地缘政治竞争以及反对超全球化的强烈反对改变了全球经济格局，并使世界经济通过贸易降低了热情好客。随着发达国家的收入增加，从制成品到服务的[需求]转变，因此制造业中全球产出的份额正在下降。即将到来的气候变化危机……减少了全球对物质商品的需求，尤其是碳足迹高的物质商品，而不是服务，而不是服务……进一步的不利发展中国家……</p><p>虽然制造业将仍然是大多数国家的重要部门，但我们认为，在东亚和过去的其他成功经济体中，它不可能是经济增长的主角……[t]他以出口为导向的工业化策略过去[现在将]不太可行和有效。我们在本文中为一项具有两个关键的插脚的战略争论：对绿色过渡和生产率提高的投资提高了吸收劳动力，主要是非交易服务。</p></blockquote><p>斯蒂格利茨（Stiglitz）一直在<a href="https://academic.oup.com/book/39562/chapter/339437881">提出这样的论点</a>。但是对于罗德里克（Rodrik）来说，新论文代表了他2015年论文以外的两个重要演变。</p><p>首先，罗德里克（Rodrik）在2015年的论文中写道：“亚洲国家和制造商在很大程度上与那些（去工业化]趋势的出口商完全隔离开来”。但是在最近的文章中，罗德里克（Rodrik）和斯蒂格利茨（Stiglitz）认为，工业化仅适用于<em>东亚</em>。目前尚不清楚他们是否将东南亚包括在定义中。但是无论如何，虽然罗德里克（Rodrik，2015年）免除了南亚（一个19.2亿人的地区），但他的假设是关于早产的去工业化的假设，罗德里克和斯蒂格利兹（2024年）不认为印度，孟加拉国，因此可以脱颖而出。与中国实现的相似。</p><p>其次，罗德里克（Rodrik）在2015年的论文中认为，技术（即自动制造）只是<em>富裕国家</em>（而不是贫穷国家）去工业化的原因。原因是，由于贫穷国家与富裕国家的经济体相比，自动化的制造业只允许他们向富裕国家出售<em>更多东西</em>，但尽管自动化自动化，也会导致更多的工厂就业。</p><p>这个论点总是有点值得怀疑的。例如，印度和印度尼西亚的国内市场非常大，尽管收入水平还远远不如发达的收入水平。但是无论如何，Rodrik和Stiglitz（2024）似乎完全丢弃了Rodrik（2015）的论点。他们现在认为，自动化将成为贫穷国家和富人的去工业化的力量。</p><p>就我个人而言，我认为这两个新论点都可以使用更强大的理由。我想知道为什么罗德里克（Rodrik）和斯蒂格利茨（Stiglitz）认为印度从根本上无力脱颖而出。我想知道为什么他们认为制造业的自动化将比1980年代更限制贫穷国家的工业化前景。</p><p>我在本文中遇到的另一个基本问题是，它将经济发展的两个截然不同的目标（<em>增长</em>和<em>就业）</em>融为一体。 Rodrik and Stiglitz argue at length that manufacturing won&#39;t be capable of <em>employing very many people</em> in poor countries going forward. But that is very different than arguing that manufacturing will be less important for <em>raising living standards</em> .</p><p> Just as an illustration, consider the US in the 1990s. Manufacturing&#39;s share of GDP rose slightly, while its share of employment went down by almost a quarter compared to 1987: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:56964,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4581a399-bee1-4291-89b9-7ebf42a18932_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> This difference was due to automation. Automation allows you to produce the same amount with fewer workers — it&#39;s exactly what allows manufacturing&#39;s contribution to GDP to decouple from its contribution to employment.</p><p> So while automation of manufacturing might make it less of a job creator for countries like India, it&#39;s a huge jump to conclude that it&#39;s therefore unimportant to the economy. It&#39;s possible that robotic factories, tended by a few engineers, will be an important source of revenue generation for developing countries. That revenue will then be spread around locally via <em><a href="https://eml.berkeley.edu/~moretti/multipliers.pdf">local multiplier effects</a></em> — the people who work at and who own the factories will spend their earnings locally, and each manufacturing job will create some larger number of other jobs in exactly the kind of nontradable services that Rodrik and Stiglitz want. That is exactly how it happens in America today, and it&#39;s difficult to see why India wouldn&#39;t work the same.</p><p> Now, there are a couple of difficulties with this. One is inequality. If automation leads to a few smart engineers making all the money and everyone else being poor, it&#39;ll require radical redistribution policies to spread around the fruits of economic growth. But this is just as true for rich countries as for poor ones. And Latin America&#39;s progress against inequality should give us hope that we can handle whatever automation throws at us.</p><p> A subtler problem is <em>learning</em> . Productivity growth comes from learning new technologies and new business models. In a world where factories employ very few people, those factories won&#39;t be as useful as <em>schools</em> for workers. Factory work might serve an important role in teaching a whole population how to work hard, show up on time, manage a modern workplace, and so on — skills that might also come in handy in the service sector. In fact, Ha-Joon Chang believes this is a key reason why manufacturing is key. So without labor-intensive manufacturing, countries might need to come up with other ways of teaching their people to be more industrious.</p><p> But I think these are secondary concerns. While Rodrik and Stiglitz have a point about manufacturing <em>employment</em> , raising living standards is ultimately far more important than giving everyone something to do.</p><p> My final criticism of Rodrik and Stiglitz&#39; paper is that it tosses out something tried-and-true in favor of something speculative and poorly specified. Rodrik and Stiglitz talk in very general terms about things like “strategic dialogue”, “policy coordination”, and “institutions” to support a new kind of industrial policy focused on nontradable services. But the picture is very vague. In contrast, promoting manufactured exports is something that countries have a pretty good idea of how to do by now.</p><p> And if we look at the countries that are developing rapidly at this very moment, we see them following a fairly traditional strategy of industrialization. <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/vietnam-its-time-to-level-up">Vietnam</a> is a good example, but <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/bangladesh-is-the-new-asian-tiger">my favorite example is Bangladesh</a> .</p><p> Over the past few decades, Bangladesh has had one of the smoothest growth paths of any country. It is still poor, and it hasn&#39;t grown as fast as China, but it has tripled its per capita GDP since 1995, making big strides against absolute poverty in the process: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png" width="702" height="505.16470588235296" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:734,&quot;width&quot;:1020,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:702,&quot;bytes&quot;:71647,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F35e7f5c4-303c-4bba-8d2f-478b256bcc20_1020x734.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> And despite not being in East Asia, it has accomplished this feat using the kind of structural transition toward manufacturing that Rodrik and Stiglitz claim will be impossible going forward: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg" width="708" height="543.2597402597403" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:709,&quot;width&quot;:924,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:708,&quot;bytes&quot;:36907,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2892d440-eb6c-4e7e-b808-e476410e3c89_924x709.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NV.IND.MANF.ZS?locations=BD">世界银行</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>This isn&#39;t quite an economic “miracle” yet, but if it goes on for much longer, it will be.</p><p> How did Bangladesh pull this off? I gave a lot of credit to the country&#39;s industrial policy when <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/bangladesh-is-the-new-asian-tiger">I blogged about it</a> back in 2021, but <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/dpr.12750">Beyer and Wacker (2023)</a> have a much more systematic approach. They conclude that Bangladesh made “good enough” policy across a wide variety of areas: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg" width="870" height="549" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:549,&quot;width&quot;:870,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:43160,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbfc1c64c-87e1-471c-b661-2a5df453c570_870x549.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/epdf/10.1111/dpr.12750">Beyer &amp; Wacker (2023)</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> Bangladesh encouraged FDI, built a bunch of infrastructure, maintained political and macroeconomic stability, stayed open to trade, and so on. Pretty traditional stuff. But Beyer and Wacker admit that this can&#39;t explain everything about Bangladesh&#39;s outperformance. There&#39;s a big “residual” in their growth accounting framework. And Bangladesh&#39;s last major policy reforms were decades ago; most countries would have slowed down by now, but Bangladesh has not.</p><p> One missing piece of the puzzle might be industrial policy — of the traditional “picking winners” type. <a href="https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/190610/ban-export-led-growth-cds.pdf">A 2016 report</a> by the Asian Development Bank explains how Bangladesh promoted the garment industry:</p><blockquote><p> This transformation through garment exports did not occur in a vacuum: the government decided very early on to promote the sector and to provide incentives to get it where it needed to be…In addition to [Special Economic Zones to encourage foreign investment], a series of policies and external factors over the years contributed to the stellar performance of [garment] exports…The Multi-Fiber Arrangement, which allowed Bangladesh to import quota-free until 2005, provided the initial impetus…The policy of creating a special bonded warehouse system designated [garments] as a “100% export-oriented” industry and created a duty-free environment for the sector even though huge tariff and non-tariff barriers affected the rest of the economy. Moreover, effective taxation of earnings from [garments] was very low and income from [garment] enterprises is exempt from taxes.</p></blockquote><p> Once again, a successful development story will leave neoliberals and industrialists debating which policy had the greater effect.</p><p> But whatever its secret sauce, Bangladesh presents a stern challenge to the Rodrik-Stiglitz thesis that the days of industrialization are done. Whatever their new nontradable-services-based industrial policy ends up being, it had better be able to deliver better sustained growth than Bangladesh. Right now, not a lot of countries are clearing that bar.</p><p> In fact, Bangladesh is embedded in a larger mega-region — South and Southeast Asia, together home to 2.4 billion people — that is seeing rapid, broadly distributed growth and pockets of intense industrialization. This, I believe, is <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-next-phase-of-globalization-is">the most important development story of our time</a> . Perhaps Africa&#39;s turn will come a bit later, but South and Southeast Asia are ready <em>now</em> , and 2.4 billion people is a very large number.</p><p> In my opinion, to tell these countries to give up on industrialization right now, at the cusp of their big moment, and to refocus on nontradable services instead, would be to do them a deep disservice. Instead, I think they should keep trying the traditional model of development, taking advantage of trends like <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/decoupling-is-just-going-to-happen">friend-shoring and de-risking</a> to encourage FDI and build up their manufacturing sectors. If that model eventually breaks, then it breaks, and we find something else. But from where I&#39;m sitting, it doesn&#39;t look broken yet. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/do-poor-countries-need-a-new-development?utm_sou